<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-580-097  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 580 097.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Network World  Nov 5 1990 v7 n45 p48(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>X.400 migration strategies. (X.400 Message Handling System)(includes related articles on X.400 gateway construction and onX.400 transition planning)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Blum, Daniel.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Migrating to the X.400 Message Handling System (MHS) to manageelectronic mail is difficult because users must examine theirorganization's need for an X.400 package and the types of X.400features they prefer.andP;  A minimal, low-risk X.400 system based onthe 1984 standards provides a Message Transfer Agent (MTA) formessage relay and a User Agent for user access.andP;  While it iswidely available on the market, it offers no sophisticated messageretrieval features, electronic data interchange or security.andP;  Aluxury X.400 system, based on 1988 standards, provides additionaloptions such as Message Store, which standardizes sophisticatedmessage retrieval, alerting, forwarding, scanning and searchingprotocols.andP;  As part of the luxury model configuration, usersshould consider implementing an X.500 directory since multivendorelectronic mail can be difficult to use.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     X.400 ProtocolSoftware MigrationStrategic PlanningElectronic Mail SystemsStandardsSystem SelectionPacket Switching.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Test-driving X.400. (table)X.400 operational concerns. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>